Problem 5¶

1) What is the relationship between PCA and SVD?

2) Derive Fisher discriminant analysis from scratch.

3) Explain how SVD can do low rank approximation.

Solution 5¶

1)

Any real symmetric and positive definite matrix $B$ has a eigen decompositon

$$B=S\Sigma S^T$$

A real matrix $A_{(m\times n)}$ , where $m > n$ , has the decomposition $$A=U \Sigma V^T$$

From $A$ (skinny and full rank) we can construct positive-definite symmetric matrices, $ATA$

$$A^{T}A=V^{T}U^{T}U \Sigma V^{T}=V \Sigma^{T} \Sigma V^{T}$$

PCA by SVD

$$B=A^{T}A=V \Sigma^{T} \Sigma V^{T}=VΛV^{T}$$

Note tha in PCA,

$$VSV^{T}(where S=\frac{1}{m}X^{T}X=(\frac{X}{\sqrt(m)})^{T}\frac{X}{\sqrt{m}}=A^{T}A)$$

2)

sample mean $\mu=\sum_{x_{(i)}\in C}^{n} x_{i}$ , sample variance $\frac{1}{n-1}\sum_{x_{(i)}\in C}^{n} (x_{i}-\mu )(x_{i}-\mu )^{T}$ projected mean $E[\hat{y}\mid x \in C] = \mu ^{T}w$ , projected variance $var[\hat{y}\mid x \in C] = \omega ^{T}S\omega$ for 2 classes,

$$\underset{\omega}{\max} \frac{\text{seperation of projected means }}{\text{sum of within class variances}} \implies \underset{\omega}{\max} \frac{(\mu_{0}^{T}\omega-\mu_{1}^{T}\omega)^{2}}{n_{0}\omega^{T}S_{0}\omega+n_{1}\omega^{T}S_{1}\omega} $$

$$J(\omega)= \frac{((\mu_{0}^{T}-\mu_{1}^{T})\omega)^{2}}{\omega^{T}(n_{0}S_{0}+n_{1}S_{1})\omega} = \frac{(m^{T}\omega)}{\omega^{T}\sum\omega} $$

$$m=\mu^{T}_{0}−\mu^{T}_{1}$$$$\sum=n_{0}S_{0}+n_{1}S_{1}=R^{T}R$$$$u=Rω\Rightarrow\omega=R^{-1}u$$$$J(u)=\frac{(m^{T}R{−1}u)^{2}}{\omega^{T}R^{T}R\omega}=\frac{((R^{−T}m)^{T}\frac{u}{\left\|u \right\|})}{u^{T}u}=((R^{-T}m)^{T}\frac{u}{∥u∥})^{2} $$$$J(u)=((R^{−T}m)^{T}\frac{u}{∥u∥})^{2} \;\; \text{is maximum, when} \; u=aR^{−T}m$$$$u=aR^{−T}m=aR^{−T}(\mu_{0}−\mu_{1})$$$$\omega=R^{−1}u=aR^{−1}R^{-T}(\mu_{0}−\mu_{1})=a(R^{T}R)^{−1}(\mu_{0}-\mu_{1})=a\sum^{−1}(\mu_{0}−\mu_{1})$$$$\omega=a(n_{0}S_{0}+n_{1}S_{1})^{−1}(\mu_{0}−\mu_{1})$$

3)

by SVD,

$$A=UΣ V^{T}$$


In order to compress $A$ without losing too much information of $A$ , we can consider that the large singular values ($\sigma$) has large information of $A$ because the singular value ($\sigma_i$) is the scaling factor corresponding to unit vector $u_i$


$A=UΣ V^{T}$can be approximated about the large singular values, it is a low rank approximation as the dimension reduction

$$A=U_{r}Σ_{r} V_{r}^{T} = \sum_{i=1}^{r}\sigma_{i}u_{i}v_{i}^{T} (r\leq n) $$

Consider the following matrix:


$$ \begin{align*} A = \begin{bmatrix} -1 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & -1 & 1 \\ \end{bmatrix} \end{align*} $$

(a) Compute the Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) of matrix $A$ using python.

import numpy as np
A = np.array([[-1, 1, 0], 
              [0, -1, 1]])

[U, S, VT] = np.linalg.svd(A, full_matrices = True)

U = np.asmatrix(U)
S = np.asmatrix(np.diag(S))
VT = np.asmatrix(VT)

print(U.shape, S.shape, VT.shape, '\n')
print(U, '\n')
print(S, '\n')
print(VT)

(b) In this time, solve it with your own hand (i.e, Do SVD by hands).


$$\begin{align*} det \left(A^TA - \lambda I \right) &= \begin{bmatrix}\ 1 - \lambda & -1 & 0 \\ -1 & 2 - \lambda & -1 \\ 0 & -1 & 1 - \lambda \\ \end{bmatrix} \\ & = (1 - \lambda)^2(2 - \lambda) - (1 - \lambda) - (1 - \lambda) \\ & = (1 - \lambda)\left((1 - \lambda)(2 - \lambda) - 2 \right) \\ & = (1 - \lambda)\lambda(\lambda - 3) = 0 \end{align*}$$

Thus, we have $\lambda = 3, 1, 0.$ Therefore, the singular values are: $\sqrt{3}, 1, 0.$

To determine V, we solve the eigenvalue-eigenvector problems. For $\lambda = 3:$


$$\begin{align*} \begin{bmatrix}\ -2 & -1 & 0 \\ -1 & -1 & -1 \\ 0 & -1 & -2 \\ \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \\ \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -2x -y \\ -x -y -z \\ -y -2z \\ \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ \end{bmatrix} \end{align*}$$

Thus we can set $\begin{bmatrix} x & y & z \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & -2 & 1 \end{bmatrix}^T,$ but we need to normalize it to have a unit length.
Thus we have $v_1 = \sqrt{6}^{-1}\begin{bmatrix} 1 & -2 & 1 \end{bmatrix}^T.$
For $\lambda = 1:$


$$\begin{align*} \begin{bmatrix}\ 0 & -1 & 0 \\ -1 & 1 & -1 \\ 0 & -1 & 0 \\ \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \\ \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -y \\ -x +y -z \\ -y \\ \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ \end{bmatrix} \end{align*}$$

Thus we can set $\begin{bmatrix} x & y & z \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 & -1 \end{bmatrix}^T,$ and after the normalization, it becomes $v_2 = \sqrt{2}^{-1}\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 & -1 \end{bmatrix}^T.$

For $\lambda = 1:$


$$\begin{align*} \begin{bmatrix}\ 1 & -1 & 0 \\ -1 & 2 & -1 \\ 0 & -1 & 1 \\ \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \\ \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} x - y \\ -x + 2y - z \\ - y + z \\ \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ \end{bmatrix} \end{align*}$$

Thus we can set $\begin{bmatrix} x & y & z \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 1 & 1 \end{bmatrix}^T,$ and after the normalization, it becomes $v_3 = \sqrt{3}^{-1}\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 1 & 1 \end{bmatrix}^T.$

Now, to compute U, we use the formula: $u_j = \frac{1}{\sigma_j}Av_j$ for $\sigma_j \ne 0.$ Thus,


$$\begin{align*} u_1 = \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\begin{bmatrix}\ -1 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & -1 & 1 \\ \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 1/\sqrt{6} \\ -2/\sqrt{6} \\ 1/\sqrt{6} \\ \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -1/\sqrt{2} \\ 1/\sqrt{2} \\ \end{bmatrix} \end{align*}$$
$$\begin{align*} u_2 = \frac{1}{1}\begin{bmatrix}\ -1 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & -1 & 1 \\ \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 1/\sqrt{2} \\ -0 \\ -1/\sqrt{2} \\ \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -1/\sqrt{2} \\ -1/\sqrt{2} \\ \end{bmatrix} \end{align*}$$

Thus the SVD of A is:
$$\begin{align*} \begin{bmatrix} -1 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & -1 & 1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -1/\sqrt{2} & -1/\sqrt{2} \\ 1/\sqrt{2} & -1/\sqrt{2} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} \sqrt{3} & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 1/\sqrt{6} & 1/\sqrt{2} & 1/\sqrt{3} \\ -2/\sqrt{6} & 0 & 1/\sqrt{3} \\ 1/\sqrt{6} & -1/\sqrt{2} & 1/\sqrt{3} \end{bmatrix}^T \end{align*}$$

(c) Compute the rank 1 approximation of matrix $A$ by hands.


$$\begin{align*} \sigma_1u_1v_1^T &= \sqrt{3}\begin{bmatrix} -1/\sqrt{2} \\ 1/\sqrt{2} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 1/\sqrt{6} & -2/\sqrt{6} & 1/\sqrt{6} \end{bmatrix} \\ &= \frac{\sqrt{3}}{\sqrt{2} \sqrt{6}} \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 1 & -2 & 1 \end{bmatrix} \\ &= \frac{1}{2} \begin{bmatrix} -1 & 2 & -1 \\ 1 & -2 & 1 \end{bmatrix} \\ &= \begin{bmatrix} -1/2 & 1 & -1/2 \\ 1/2 & -1 & 1/2 \end{bmatrix} \\ \end{align*}$$

(b) Load the image into grayscale and reshape each picture as (row $\times$ col, 1) shape, then stack them to form matrix $A$ with a shape of (row $\times$ col, 20).

In [4]:
for i in range(20):
    image = cv2.imread(f'./image_files/capimage_{i}.jpg')
    image = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
    if i == 0:
        orig_shape = image.shape
        arr = image[:,:]
        flat_arr = arr.reshape(orig_shape[0] * orig_shape[1], 1)
        flat_vector = flat_arr
    else:
        arr = image[:,:]
        flat = arr.reshape(orig_shape[0] * orig_shape[1], 1)
        flat_vector = np.hstack([flat_vector, flat])

A = flat_vector

(e) Explain why we have the above result.

Decompose $A$ into $U, S, V$ by applying SVD method. After that, reconstruct $\hat{A}$ by low rank approximation for $rank = 1$. Because the background is almost the same for each frame, the information will be contained in $\hat A[:,0]$.
